Table 1. Some Recently Reported MOF-Stabilized SACs by Using Various Fabrication Strategies and Their Applications

| metal | catalyst | fabrication strategy | application | durability | ref |
|-------|----------|-----------------------|--------------|-------------|-----|
| Ru<sub>1</sub> | Ru@ZIF-8 | pore confinement | hydrogenation of phenylacetylene | 5 recycles | [26] |
| Ni<sub>1</sub> | Ni-AIM | metal node stabilization | hydrogenation of ethylene | 2 weeks | [27] |
| V<sub>1</sub> | Hf-MOF-808-V; Zr-MOF-808-V | metal node stabilization | oxidation of 4-methoxybenzyl alcohol | 3 recycles | [28] |
| Co<sub>1</sub> | Ti<sub>8</sub>-BDC-CoCl | metal node stabilization | hydrogenation of arene | 10 recycles | [29] |
| Cu<sub>1</sub> | Cu/UiO-66 | metal node stabilization | CO oxidation | 20 h | [30] |
| Ir<sub>1</sub>/Pt<sub>1</sub> | HNTM-Ir/Pt | coordination stabilization | photocatalytic H<sub>2</sub> evolution | 3 recycles | [31] |
| Co<sub>1</sub> | MOF-525-Co | coordination stabilization | photocatalytic CO<sub>2</sub> reduction | 3 recycles | [32] |
| Pt<sub>1</sub> | Pt-Al-TCPP | coordination stabilization | photocatalytic H<sub>2</sub> evolution | 4 recycles | [33] |
| Pt<sub>1</sub> | Pt SA-MNSs | coordination stabilization | photocatalytic H<sub>2</sub> evolution | 4 recycles | [34] |
